segment.source: AXE.exe is a command-line tool that's installed with the Windows Assessment Toolkit.
segment.target: AXE.exe is a command-line tool that's installed with the Windows Assessment Toolkit.

segment.source: You can use this set of command-line options to automate jobs from a script and minimize resource usage.
segment.target: You can use this set of command-line options to automate jobs from a script and minimize resource usage.

segment.source: A job is one or more assessments run at one time on a computer.
segment.target: A job is one or more assessments run at one time on a computer.

segment.source: You can't use the command-line options to compose a job.
segment.target: You can't use the command-line options to compose a job.

segment.source: You should create, modify, and save a job by using the Windows Assessment Console.
segment.target: You should create, modify, and save a job by using the Windows Assessment Console.

segment.source: By default, jobs are saved to the %USERPROFILE%DocumentsWindows Assessment ConsoleJobs folder.
segment.target: By default, jobs are saved to the %USERPROFILE%DocumentsWindows Assessment ConsoleJobs folder.

segment.source: By default, AXE.exe is installed to:
segment.target: By default, AXE.exe is installed to:

segment.source: %PROGRAMFILES%Windows Kits10 Assessment and Deployment KitWindows Assessment Toolkitarchitecture
segment.target: %PROGRAMFILES%Windows Kits10 Assessment and Deployment KitWindows Assessment Toolkitarchitecture

segment.source: Where architecture is either x86 or amd64.
segment.target: Where architecture is either x86 or amd64.

segment.source: The following table provides a description for how you can use each option.
segment.target: The following table provides a description for how you can use each option.

segment.source: These options aren't case-sensitive.
segment.target: These options aren't case-sensitive.

segment.target: Option

segment.source: JobFile
segment.target: JobFile

segment.source: Specifies the job file that you want to run.
segment.target: Specifies the job file that you want to run.

segment.source: The path of the job file can be a relative path.
segment.target: The path of the job file can be a relative path.

segment.source: If the job is in the directory that you're running AXE.exe from, no path is required.
segment.target: If the job is in the directory that you're running AXE.exe from, no path is required.

segment.source: By default, when you create a job in the Windows Assessment Console, it's saved in the %USERPROFILE%\Documents\Windows Assessment Console\Jobs folder.
segment.target: By default, when you create a job in the Windows Assessment Console, it's saved in the %USERPROFILE%\Documents\Windows Assessment Console\Jobs folder.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: This option is required if no other parameter that performs an action is specified.
segment.target: This option is required if no other parameter that performs an action is specified.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /Timeoutseconds
segment.target: /Timeoutseconds

segment.source: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, that the job will wait for another job to finish before it exits with an error.
segment.target: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, that the job will wait for another job to finish before it exits with an error.

segment.source: The default is zero, which means that the job will exit immediately if another job is already running.
segment.target: The default is zero, which means that the job will exit immediately if another job is already running.

segment.source: This is an optional parameter.
segment.target: This is an optional parameter.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /NoPublish
segment.target: /NoPublish

segment.source: Specifies not to publish the results file to the location that's specified in the job file.
segment.target: Specifies not to publish the results file to the location that's specified in the job file.

segment.source: When you use this option, the results are saved to the default location, %LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\Axe\Results.
segment.target: When you use this option, the results are saved to the default location, %LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\Axe\Results.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /PublishPathDirectory
segment.target: /PublishPathDirectory

segment.source: Specifies the path of a folder to publish the results file to.
segment.target: Specifies the path of a folder to publish the results file to.

segment.source: This overrides the publication path, ResultsPublishPath, that's specified in the job file.
segment.target: This overrides the publication path, ResultsPublishPath, that's specified in the job file.

segment.source: This parameter is ignored if it's combined with /NoPublish.
segment.target: This parameter is ignored if it's combined with /NoPublish.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /RemoveRestart
segment.target: /RemoveRestart

segment.source: Specifies that any existing, pending job-restart task should be removed.
segment.target: Specifies that any existing, pending job-restart task should be removed.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: The /JobFile option isn't needed when you use this option.
segment.target: The /JobFile option isn't needed when you use this option.

segment.source: When you run a job, the assessment creates a task to restart the job if there's a system failure, like a loss of power.
segment.target: When you run a job, the assessment creates a task to restart the job if there's a system failure, like a loss of power.

segment.source: When you use this option, the task is removed from the Task Scheduler.
segment.target: When you use this option, the task is removed from the Task Scheduler.

segment.source: If no job-restart task is pending, the assessment will return an error to inform you that the task doesn't exist.
segment.target: If no job-restart task is pending, the assessment will return an error to inform you that the task doesn't exist.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /NoWarnings
segment.target: /NoWarnings

segment.source: Suppresses warning messages.
segment.target: Suppresses warning messages.

segment.source: This is an optional parameter.
segment.target: This is an optional parameter.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /Pause
segment.target: /Pause

segment.source: Pauses AXE.exe after the job finishes, to wait for you to press a key.
segment.target: Pauses AXE.exe after the job finishes, to wait for you to press a key.

segment.source: You can then see any errors or other information in the console before AXE.exe exits and the console closes.
segment.target: You can then see any errors or other information in the console before AXE.exe exits and the console closes.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /JobParameter Param=value
segment.target: /JobParameter Param=value

segment.source: Specifies a value to override a job parameter that may exist in the job manifest.
segment.target: Specifies a value to override a job parameter that may exist in the job manifest.

segment.source: This is an optional parameter.
segment.target: This is an optional parameter.

segment.source: You can use it up to 100 times to specify multiple job parameters.
segment.target: You can use it up to 100 times to specify multiple job parameters.

segment.source: If duplicate job parameter names appear, the assessment uses the last one.
segment.target: If duplicate job parameter names appear, the assessment uses the last one.

segment.source: The /PublishPath option takes precedence over setting the ResultsPublishPath job parameter with this option.
segment.target: The /PublishPath option takes precedence over setting the ResultsPublishPath job parameter with this option.

segment.source: Example:
segment.target: Example:

segment.source: /DisplayLogpath_to_AXE_ETL_log_file
segment.target: /DisplayLogpath_to_AXE_ETL_log_file

segment.source: Displays the content of the Event Trace Log (ETL) files that AXE.exe uses for logging.
segment.target: Displays the content of the Event Trace Log (ETL) files that AXE.exe uses for logging.

segment.source: You must specify the path of the AXE.exe ETL files.
segment.target: You must specify the path of the AXE.exe ETL files.

segment.source: The location of the log files appears in the console when a job runs.
segment.target: The location of the log files appears in the console when a job runs.

segment.source: The file name may contain wildcard characters.
segment.target: The file name may contain wildcard characters.

segment.source: The default location of the log file is %LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\Axe\Logs\GUID, where GUID is the GUID that's generated randomly for each new job.
segment.target: The default location of the log file is %LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\Axe\Logs\GUID, where GUID is the GUID that's generated randomly for each new job.

segment.source: The job results file in the SessionLogFiles node also contains the full location.
segment.target: The job results file in the SessionLogFiles node also contains the full location.

segment.source: This node specifies all of the log files.
segment.target: This node specifies all of the log files.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: All of the ETL files are automatically converted into a single AxeLog.txt file that's saved in the results directory.
segment.target: All of the ETL files are automatically converted into a single AxeLog.txt file that's saved in the results directory.

segment.source: You can open this file by using Notepad.
segment.target: You can open this file by using Notepad.

segment.target: Running a job at the command prompt uses fewer resources and has less impact on performance metrics.

segment.target: You can use command-line options to automate a job.

segment.target: Command-line options provide additional parameters that aren't available in the Windows Assessment Console.
